10.
\f1  
\f2 Provide clear explanations to patients about their condition and the reasons for your management plan.\
11.
\f1  
\f2 Always consider the impact of the patient's occupation, especially for conditions that may affect their ability to work safely (e.g., driving occupations).\
12.
\f1  
\f2 Don't rely solely on classic textbook descriptions. Be prepared for variations in presentation and atypical cases.\
13.
\f1  
\f2 Remember that the urgency of referral for TIA depends on the patient's occupation, especially if it involves driving.\
14.
\f1  
\f2 For urgent referrals, don't specify an exact timeframe to the patient unless asked. If asked, you can say it usually takes about 4-6 weeks.\
15.
\f1  
\f2 Be aware that a 2-week urgent referral is typically reserved for suspected cancer pathways.\
16.
\f1  
\f2 When explaining CPAP for sleep apnea, mention that it might be uncomfortable at first but patients usually adapt over time.\
17.
\f1  
\f2 Always mention the increased risk of heart-related conditions like heart attacks or strokes if conditions like sleep apnea or TIA are left untreated.\
18.
\f1  
\f2 Avoid dismissing symptoms even if they seem minor. Take all reports seriously, especially when accompanied by other concerning symptoms.\
19.
\f1  
\f2 If a spouse or family member is mentioned as noticing symptoms, involve them in the discussion if present, or suggest they accompany the patient to future appointments.\
20.
\f1  
\f2 Be thorough in your history taking. Don't forget to ask about recent weight changes, alcohol consumption, smoking, and any previous surgeries or injuries that might be relevant.\
21.
\f1  
\f2 When discussing lifestyle changes, be specific and realistic. Offer concrete suggestions for improvement rather than general advice.\
22.
\f1  
\f2 Remember to arrange follow-up appointments to discuss test results and monitor progress, even for conditions that may seem less urgent.\
